  "text": "Level-The effects of metformin on Sepp1 expression in H4IIEC3 hepatocytes were examined. Metformin suppressed Sepp1 mRNA expression in a concentration-and time-dependent manner, similarly to G6pc and Pck1, which encode representative gluconeogenic enzymes glucose-6-phosphatase and phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase 1, respectively ( Fig. 1, A  and B) . These results are consistent with a previous report using rat primary hepatocytes [CITATION_1] . Next, the effects of metformin on SEPP1 promoter activity were examined. The human SEPP1 promoter region was cloned to a luciferase reporter vector as reported previously [CITATION_2] . The present sequence completely corresponded to the reference sequence of the National Center for Biotechnology Information, but it missed one thymidine against the sequence of the previous report (accession number Y12262) (supplemental Fig. S1 ). Similar to the mRNA results, metformin suppressed SEPP1 promoter activity in a concentration-and time-dependent manner ( Fig. 1, C and D) , suggesting that it directly decreases SEPP1 transcriptional activity in H4IIEC3 hepatocytes.",
